# ===================================================
# Memory System: Dynamo Knowledge Graph CLI
# ===================================================

## Dynamo CLI for Memory Operations
- All memory operations go through the `dynamo` CLI at `~/.claude/dynamo/dynamo.cjs`
- Run commands via: `node ~/.claude/dynamo/dynamo.cjs <command> [options]`
- The global toggle controls all memory access -- if Dynamo is disabled, all commands error

## Available Commands

### Memory Operations
| Command | Description | Use When |
|---------|-------------|----------|
| `dynamo search <query>` | Search knowledge graph for facts and entities | Looking up what you know about a topic, recalling decisions |
| `dynamo search <query> --facts` | Search for facts (relationships) only | When you need specific relationship data |
| `dynamo search <query> --nodes` | Search for entity nodes only | Finding specific entities, people, tools, concepts |
| `dynamo remember <content>` | Store a memory in the knowledge graph | User says "remember this", storing decisions/patterns/prefs |
| `dynamo recall` | Retrieve recent episodes | Reviewing what was stored recently |
| `dynamo edge <uuid>` | Inspect a specific relationship | Getting details about a particular fact |
| `dynamo forget <uuid>` | Delete an episode | User says "forget this", removing incorrect info |
| `dynamo forget --edge <uuid>` | Delete a specific relationship | Removing a specific incorrect fact |
| `dynamo clear --scope <scope> --confirm` | Clear all data for a scope | DESTRUCTIVE -- only on explicit user request |

### Session Management
| Command | Description | Use When |
|---------|-------------|----------|
| `dynamo session list` | List recent sessions | Reviewing session history |
| `dynamo session view <id>` | View a specific session | Reading session details |
| `dynamo session label <id> <label>` | Label a session | Organizing sessions |
| `dynamo session backfill` | Backfill session names via Haiku | Naming unnamed sessions |

### System Operations
| Command | Description | Use When |
|---------|-------------|----------|
| `dynamo start` | Start the Graphiti Docker stack with health wait | Starting Dynamo for a session |
| `dynamo stop` | Stop the Graphiti Docker stack (preserves data) | Shutting down when done |
| `dynamo install` | Deploy Dynamo to ~/.claude/dynamo/ (backup, copy, config, hooks, health check) | Initial install or reinstall |
| `dynamo rollback` | Restore previous version from backup | Reverting a bad update or install |
| `dynamo check-update` | Check for available Dynamo updates (current vs latest) | Checking if a newer version exists |
| `dynamo update` | Update Dynamo to latest version (backup, pull, migrate, verify, auto-rollback) | Upgrading to a new release |
| `dynamo sync` | Bidirectional sync between repo and live deployment | After editing source files in repo |
| `dynamo toggle on\|off` | Enable or disable Dynamo globally | Maintenance or troubleshooting |
| `dynamo status` | Show Dynamo enabled/disabled state | Checking if Dynamo is active |
| `dynamo version` | Show Dynamo version | Checking current version |

### Diagnostics
| Command | Description | Use When |
|---------|-------------|----------|
| `dynamo health-check` | Run 6-stage health check | Quick system health verification |
| `dynamo diagnose` | Run all 13 diagnostic stages | Deep system inspection when something is wrong |
| `dynamo verify-memory` | Run 6 pipeline checks | Verifying memory write/read/scope pipeline |
| `dynamo test` | Run the Dynamo test suite | After code changes |

## Command Options
- `--scope <scope>`: Memory scope (default: global). Values: `global`, `project-<name>`, `session-<ts>`, `task-<desc>`
- `--format json`: Structured JSON output for programmatic processing
- `--format raw`: Full source content from graph for deep context
- Default: Human-readable text output

## Output Behavior
- Human-readable output goes to stderr
- JSON and raw output goes to stdout
- This means `dynamo search "query" --format json` can be piped to other tools
- Human-facing commands (without --format) display to stderr for Claude's context window

## How to Choose Format
- Use default (no flag) for conversational responses to the user
- Use `--format json` when you need to parse the response programmatically
- Use `--format raw` when you need the complete, unfiltered graph data

## Scoping
| Scope | Format | Contents |
|-------|--------|----------|
| Global | `global` | User prefs, workflow patterns, coding style |
| Project | `project-<name>` | Architecture, decisions, conventions |
| Session | `session-<timestamp>` | Conversation summaries |
| Task | `task-<descriptor>` | Task requirements, progress |

**Note:** Scope values must contain only alphanumeric characters, dashes, or underscores (no colons).

## CRITICAL: Flat-File Memory is DISABLED
- Do NOT use the auto memory directory (~/.claude/projects/*/memory/)
- Do NOT create or update MEMORY.md files
- ALL memory operations go through Dynamo CLI or are handled by hooks

## How Memory Works (Automatic -- Zero User Intervention)
Hooks inject context automatically at key lifecycle points:
- **SessionStart**: Global preferences + project context + recent sessions
- **UserPromptSubmit**: Semantic search augments every prompt with relevant memories
- **PostToolUse (Write/Edit)**: File changes captured to knowledge graph
- **PreCompact**: Key knowledge preserved before context window compression
- **Stop**: Session summarized and stored

## Using Injected Context
When you see `[GRAPHITI MEMORY CONTEXT]` or `[RELEVANT MEMORY]`:
- This is curated context from the knowledge graph -- use it
- Don't re-query for information already injected
- If context seems stale or insufficient, run `dynamo search` directly

## Explicit Memory Operations
- **"Remember this"**: `dynamo remember "<content>" --scope <scope>`
- **"What do you know about X"**: `dynamo search "<query>" --scope <scope>`
- **"Forget this"**: `dynamo forget <uuid>` (get UUID from search results)
- **Architectural decisions**: Proactively store via `dynamo remember` in project scope
- **Discovered patterns**: Store in project scope

## Graphiti Infrastructure
- Docker stack: `~/.claude/graphiti/docker-compose.yml`
- Start: `dynamo start`
- Stop: `dynamo stop`
- Health: `dynamo health-check`
- Neo4j browser: `http://localhost:7475`

## Troubleshooting

### "Dynamo is disabled" error
- Check status: `dynamo status`
- Re-enable: `dynamo toggle on`
- For development with Dynamo off globally: set `DYNAMO_DEV=1` in your environment

### Stack not starting
- Run `dynamo health-check` to identify which stage fails
- Check Docker is running: `docker ps`
- Check container status: `docker compose -f ~/.claude/graphiti/docker-compose.yml ps`
- View logs: `docker logs graphiti-mcp --tail 50`
- Full restart: `dynamo stop && dynamo start`

### Stale session IDs
- Restart Claude Code entirely -- MCP client caches session IDs

### Hook errors
- Check error log: `cat ~/.claude/dynamo/hook-errors.log`
- Log auto-rotates at 1MB
- Hooks always exit 0 (never block Claude Code) -- errors are logged, not thrown

### Health check failures
- Run deep diagnostics: `dynamo diagnose`
- This runs 13 stages covering Docker, Neo4j, API, MCP, env vars, and more
- Each stage reports PASS/FAIL/SKIP with details

### Memory not persisting
- Verify pipeline: `dynamo verify-memory`
- This runs 6 checks: write, read, scope isolation, sessions, and round-trip

## Maintenance

### Updating Dynamo
- Check for updates: `dynamo check-update`
- Update to latest version: `dynamo update` (creates backup, pulls code, runs migrations, verifies health, auto-rolls back on failure)
- Or manual: `cd <repo-dir> && git pull` then `dynamo install`

### Checking Version
- `dynamo version` shows current version
- `dynamo check-update` shows current vs latest version

### After Config Changes
- If config.json changed: `dynamo sync` or `dynamo install`
- If docker-compose.yml changed: `dynamo stop && dynamo start`
- If hooks changed: `dynamo sync` then restart Claude Code

### Stack Management
- Start: `dynamo start` (includes health wait)
- Stop: `dynamo stop` (preserves all data in Docker volumes)
- Health: `dynamo health-check`

## Component Architecture

Dynamo has three components with strict scope boundaries:

| Component | Scope | Directory | What It Handles |
|-----------|-------|-----------|-----------------|
| **Dynamo** | Orchestration | `dynamo/` | CLI router, hook dispatcher, config, shared substrate |
| **Ledger** | Memory | `ledger/` | Knowledge graph operations, search, episodes, curation, sessions, hooks |
| **Switchboard** | Operations | `switchboard/` | Install, sync, health-check, diagnose, verify-memory, stack management |

**Naming convention:** Files and functions should reflect their component. Ledger handles memory. Switchboard handles operations. Dynamo orchestrates.

**Import boundaries:** Code in each component imports only from its own scope or from `dynamo/core.cjs` (shared substrate). No cross-imports between Ledger and Switchboard.

